==English==
{{webster}}
===Etymology===
From from {{L.}} [[profanus]], properly, before the temple, i.e., without the temple, unholy; ''[[pro-]]'' before + ''[[fanum]]'' temple; via {{F.}}.

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-eɪn|-eɪn]]

===Adjective===
'''profane'''
# Not sacred or holy; not possessing peculiar sanctity; unconsecrated; hence, relating to matters other than sacred; secular; -- opposed to sacred, religious, or inspired; as, a profane place.
# Unclean; impure; polluted; unholy.
# Treating sacred things with contempt, disrespect, irreverence, or undue familiarity; irreverent; impious.  Hence, specifically; Irreverent in language; taking the name of God in vain; given to [[swear]]ing; blasphemous; as, a profane person, word, oath, or tongue.

====Synonyms====
*[[secular]]; [[temporal]]; [[worldly]]; [[unsanctified]]; [[unhallowed]]; [[unholy]]; [[irreligious]]; [[irreverent]]; [[ungodly]]; [[wicked]]; [[godless]]; [[impious]]

====Translations====
* [[German]] : [[profan]]
* [[Ido]] : [[profana]]

===Transitive verb===
'''to profane'''  ([[profanes]], [[profaned]], [[profaning]])
# To violate, as anything sacred; to treat with abuse, irreverence, obloquy, or contempt; to desecrate; to pollute; as, to profane the name of God; to profane the Scriptures, or the ordinance of God.
# To put to a wrong or unworthy use; to make a base employment of; to debase; to abuse; to defile.

===Related terms===
*[[profanation]]
*[[profanity]]

